metadata.name: Paper Cut #93
metadata.description:
Paper Cut is a p5.js layered collage composition of Truchet patterns on textured paper. 

For a description of how it was created please see my first ever fxhash article of the same name.

Use the 'r' key on the keyboard to randomise some parameters while keeping the essence of the piece the same. 

Use keys, 2, 3 and 4 to render at higher resolutions.

metadata.name: Harmonies #160
metadata.description:
Harmonies is a color palette generator created for fxhash anniversary. The generator chooses from 7 possible color harmonies "Complementary, Split-Complementary, Analogous, Triadic, Tetradic, Square, Analogous and Monochromatic" to create harmonic color palettes. When i studied colors back in time, i used to take a color or a couple of colors and paint strokes on paper with watercolors to understand and learn how they stand out together. This piece is a result of those studies.

5 stroke compositions for 'Split-Complementary, Analogous and Triadic'
3 stroke compositions for 'Tetradic, Square and Monochromatic'
3 stroke compositions for 'Complementary'
2 color mods "Saturated and Muted' and 6 rendering methods for strokes 'Random Saturated, Random Brightness, Random Brightness & Saturation, Saturation Gradient, Brightness Gradient, Brightness & Saturation Gradient'

Save image by pressing 's'
Save colors as hex array ready to be used by pressing 'p'

Created with p5.js | Murat Atimtay 2022

metadata.name: Ontologies #24
metadata.description:
A system designed to make art out of its own code. 

What is the 'artful' component of generative art - is it the algorithm's form or the aesthetics of individual outputs? Ontologies brings the code out of the shadows into the foreground, nudging the viewer to consider this system's recursive existence. 

Is there something vaguely mortal, or at least vulnerable, about a system 'aware' of its own inner workings (like a person contemplating their DNA code)? Our use of computers to express incomputable human inspiration and creativity suggests that we already see them as more than just tools or calculating machines. So who is the artist, and what is the art?

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Punktwelt #541
metadata.description:
Continuing on the theme of color perception in Farbteiler, Punktwelt is an exploration of color interaction, projection and perceived depth, and the aesthetics of simple Boolean operations on form.

Each shape is the result of a single block, a rectangular cuboid, subjected to a series of Boolean subtractions with other blocks, and rendered in parallel projection, oblique or axonometric, in the abstract landscape of the Punktwelt.

Some have horizons, some have banded or striped backgrounds. The unnatural drawing order and chromatic differences of the individual faces sometimes yields illusory or paradoxical visual geometries.

Press ’s’ to save a png. Press ’4’ to export a high resolution png. Press ’8’ to export a very high resolution png. Press ’e’ to export an SVG file (may take some time and produce large files).

Aspect ratio variations are 4:5, 5:4, 2:3, 3:2 and 1:1.

Built in Javascript with p5.js, p5.svg and csg.js.

metadata.name: Asterium #296
metadata.description:
Asterium is a token that will grow with you, for an entire year. Changing and morphing over time to eventually reach its equilibrium.

It is a token where I try to symbolize the journey of life.
Where looking back is the best way to look forward.
Where looking into the future is not a possibility.
Where each day is as uncertain as the next.

A token that will surprise you and have its ups and downs as it grows over time.



Pricing:
Dutch auction 64-16-8, where anybody that picks one up at 64 tez gets a print of how their galaxy looks on any day from the present to day 0. Meaning you can claim the print at any point in the future.

The print will be printed on high quality hahnemühle torchon paper at 30x40 cm (11.81 x 15.75 in). Printed at a local print shop here in Utrecht. This paper has a rough texture to it that matches the textures of space perfectly.



Usage:
- Hover over your Asterium to view the name, date, days passed, status and render stats.
- Double press to export the current frame as a .png image.
- Use the slider at the bottom to scroll back in time to the days before today, you can go as far back as day 0 and as far forwards as today.
- The token refreshes every hour, so framing it in a digital picture frame is totally possible!

metadata.name: The Hypothetical Motherboards V2.0 #102
metadata.description:
The V2.0 fix a bug in the V1.0.
Remaining V1.0 tokes have been burned, and I will airdrop V2.0 token to the V1.0 owners.

An algorithm that combine 19 differents tiles to a unique piece that may look like a motherboard.

There are 19 different tiles design, 6 styles, 32 Color Schemes and 4 specials features.

Pieces are generated by spreading the core tiles on the canvas plus an amount of processor is added. Finally, a finishing pass is made by smartly adding connector tiles where they are needed. Connector tiles have either 1,2,3 or 4 sides to connect with.

# GENERATIVE FEATURES

## Processor count
The more processor, the rarest
- 4 processors (≃35% of chance)
- 5 processors (≃25% of chance)
- 6 processors (≃15% of chance)
- 8 processors (≃10% of chance)
- 16 processors (≃5% of chance)

## Color scheme
There are 32 different color schemes and 6 different filling style, Gradient, Textured, Stripes, Moiré, Flat and Op Art.
- randomly picked, all themes have the same probability of being picked

## Filling style
Filling are distributed as follow :
- 14 Gradient (≃45% of total)
- 7 Texture (≃21% of total)
- 6 Flat (≃18% of total)
- 3 Moiré (≃10% of total)
- 1 Stripes (≃3% of total)
- 1 Op Art (≃3% of total)

## Special Feature
3 themes have 2 special features, 18 themes have 1 special feature and 11 themes have 0 special features.

Features are distributed as follow :
- 18 color schemes are Animated (≃56% of total)
- 7 color schemes have no feature (≃21% of total)
- 4 color schemes have Grainy textures (≃12% of total)
- 2 color schemes are Alien (≃6% of total)
- 2 color schemes are Rusted (≃6% of total)
- 1 color schemes have Stars (≃3% of total)
- 1 color schemes have Heart (≃3% of total)

## Tiles density
Tiles density is calculated regarding the amount of total tiles added and will be dependent of the tiles density of the core, processor and connector and will be either "Crowded", "Filed", "Mostly Filed", "Average", "Sparse", "Very Sparse" or "Scattered"

metadata.name: LA BOUGIE 🕯 #50
metadata.description:
This work is a collection along the lines of abstract works that I produced during the last year, and this is the first generative project in the form of a collaboration with the artist's friend Arash. This is the beginning of the production of fascinating works that we have been working on for several projects for months. In the background of this piece, there is a combination of Mondrian's known works with his well-known color palette and style, and the compositions try to remember Mondrian's works and create new and different designs. This deconstruction of The style Art movement continued and flourished with his other contemporary artists; Fx Hash's one-year candle combines de Stijl's work with a new pattern that creates new compositions independent of this work.

Unique collection by ArashMp and Chistai for #fxhashturnsone
Happy birthday fx(hash)!
#fxhashturnsone

metadata.name: contrapuntos #27
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.
